  "text": "The E0505 error 'cannot move out of x because it is borrowed' is generated through a multi-layered detection and reporting chain in the Rust compiler's MIR borrow checker.\n\n**Error Detection Layer:**\nThe error originates in `compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/lib.rs` (line 1246+), specifically in the `check_access_for_conflict` function of the `MirBorrowckCtxt` struct. This function analyzes MIR statements for borrow conflicts. At lines 1361-1362, it detects when a `WriteKind::Move` operation conflicts with an active borrow (checked via the borrow kind matching on line 1324). When such a conflict is found, it calls `report_move_out_while_borrowed`.\n\n**Diagnostic Reporting Chain:**\nThe error reporting flows through three key functions:\n1. `report_move_out_while_borrowed` in `compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/diagnostics/conflict_errors.rs` (line 1533) - This function gathers information about the move and borrow locations, then calls `cannot_move_when_borrowed`\n2. `cannot_move_when_borrowed` in `compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/borrowck_errors.rs` (line 16) - This creates the diagnostic error using the `MoveBorrow` struct\n3. `MoveBorrow` struct in `compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/session_diagnostics.rs` (line 285) - This is decorated with `#[diag(borrowck_cannot_move_when_borrowed, code = E0505)]`, defining the error code\n\n**Error Message Template:**\nThe translatable error message is defined in `compiler/rustc_borrowck/messages.ftl` (lines 25-37) as `borrowck_cannot_move_when_borrowed`, which formats the message: \"cannot move out of {place} because it is borrowed\" with labels for the borrow and move locations.\n\n**Error Code Explanation:**\nThe full explanation and usage examples for E0505 are provided in `compiler/rustc_error_codes/src/error_codes/E0505.md`, which describes the conflict between borrowing and moving a value, along with recommended fixes (borrowing instead, releasing borrow before move, or implementing Copy)."
}

